{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "OHReactionLifetime",
        "description": "Atmospheric lifetime against reaction with the hydroxyl radical (OH), from Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics Ch. 2, Eq. 2.12: tau = 1/(k_OH*[OH]). OH is the dominant daytime oxidant of the troposphere, so the OH-reaction lifetime sets how long most reactive trace gases \u2014 methane, carbon monoxide, non-methane VOCs \u2014 persist in the atmosphere. This observed-only algebraic component implements two relations: an effective pseudo-first-order loss rate constant k_eff = k_OH*OH_conc (the second-order reaction X + OH collapsed onto the approximately constant ambient OH), and the lifetime tau_OH = 1/k_eff. The lifetime is jointly controlled by the species' intrinsic reactivity (k_OH, spanning four-plus decades across tropospheric trace gases) and the ambient oxidising capacity ([OH], varying with season, latitude and pollution): a species may persist for years in clean remote air and only hours in a polluted daytime plume. Purely algebraic system (no time derivatives): four variables \u2014 one parameter k_OH, one input OH_conc encoded as a parameter, two outputs k_eff and tau_OH as state \u2014 and two equations. Migrated from GasChem.jl@280ee50f src/AtmosphericLifetime.jl:264 (`OHReactionLifetime` @component).",
        "tags": [
            "gaschem",
            "atmospheric-lifetime",
            "oh-reaction",
            "hydroxyl-radical",
            "tropospheric-chemistry",
            "observed-only",
            "seinfeld-pandis"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-17T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "GasChem.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-58k2)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H., & Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd ed. Wiley. Chapter 2, Eq. 2.12 (atmospheric lifetime against OH reaction, tau = 1/(k_OH*[OH])), with the effective pseudo-first-order rate constant of Eq. 2.6. OH-reaction rate constants for CH4 and CO from the GasChem.jl AtmosphericLifetime test suite."
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "OHReactionLifetime": {
            "reference": {
                "notes": "source_ref: GasChem.jl@280ee50fbc8fb6d8bdf4b12c9ef1c506fe890551:src/AtmosphericLifetime.jl:264\n\nUpstream `OHReactionLifetime` is an MTK `@component` declaring one `@parameter` (k_OH, the second-order OH reaction rate constant), three time-indexed `@variables` (OH_conc the input OH number density; k_eff and tau_OH the two outputs), zero `@constants`, and two algebraic equations. It implements Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Ch. 2 Eq. 2.12 \u2014 the atmospheric lifetime of a trace species against removal by reaction with the hydroxyl radical, tau = 1 / (k_OH*[OH]). OH is the dominant daytime tropospheric oxidant, so this lifetime sets the persistence of most reactive trace gases (CH4, CO, non-methane VOCs). The upstream docstring notes the product k_OH*[OH] is an effective first-order rate constant 'consistent with Eq. 2.6'.\n\nVariable-classification convention: the input @variable OH_conc is encoded here as `type: parameter` because it has no defining equation within the OHReactionLifetime component itself \u2014 it is an externally-supplied ambient OH concentration. The upstream structural test `1.4 OHReactionLifetime Structure` (test/atmospheric_lifetime_test.jl) builds the raw `@named` System where OH_conc is still an `unknown`; the canonical simulate path compiles such an input-bearing component with `mtkcompile(sys; inputs=[OH_conc])`, which resolves the input @variable into a parameter. This mirrors the rig-wide convention applied by sibling oh_production.esm (input @variables O3/H2O/M encoded as `type: parameter`), ope.esm (OH/HO2/RO2/NO/NO2), and the same-source-file sibling tropospheric_budget.esm (P_n/P_a/P_c). The single declared @parameter k_OH carries `type: parameter` directly. The two output @variables k_eff and tau_OH are encoded as `type: state` \u2014 each is the LHS of exactly one algebraic equation; this matches the sibling observed-only gaschem ESM convention (ope.esm P_O3/L_NOx/OPE all `type: state`, oh_production.esm O1D/P_OH/eps_OH all `type: state`).\n\nStructural-test reproduction: upstream `1.4 OHReactionLifetime Structure` asserts the raw System carries the three variable names OH_conc/k_eff/tau_OH among `unknowns`, k_OH among `parameters`, and `length(equations) == 2`. The .esm preserves this with four declared variables (2 parameter k_OH+OH_conc, 2 state k_eff+tau_OH \u2014 together the four symbols that upstream splits into 3 unknowns + 1 parameter) and exactly two entries in `equations`.\n\nCGS->SI unit translation: the upstream Julia declares the component in CGS units \u2014 k_OH as u\"cm^3/(molec*s)\", OH_conc as u\"molec/cm^3\", k_eff as u\"s^-1\", tau_OH as u\"s\" \u2014 and carries no `default =` value on either k_OH or OH_conc. The .esm declares the two number-density-bearing quantities in SI, dropping the dimensionless `molec` count: k_OH in m^3/s and OH_conc in m^-3, matching the rig-wide SI unit vocabulary (no committed .esm uses `cm^3` or `molec`; siblings oh_production.esm and ope.esm convert the identical CGS rate-constant and number-density quantities to m^3/s and m^-3). The conversion is exact and physics-invariant for the two outputs: k_OH[m^3/s] = k_OH[cm^3/molec/s] * 1e-6 (1 cm^3 = 1e-6 m^3) and OH_conc[m^-3] = OH_conc[molec/cm^3] * 1e6 (1 cm^-3 = 1e6 m^-3), so their product k_eff = k_OH*OH_conc is unchanged (the *1e-6 and *1e6 factors cancel) and tau_OH = 1/k_eff is likewise unchanged. Both equations are unit-system-agnostic in form; only the input/parameter literals carry the conversion. Unlike sibling ope.esm \u2014 whose upstream Julia already wrote the rate constants as the SI-converted product (8.1e-12 * 1.0e-6) \u2014 the OHReactionLifetime upstream is purely CGS, so this migration introduces the conversion: the .esm encodes the clean SI literals (6.3e-21, 2.4e-19, 1.0e-16, 1.0e-20 m^3/s; 1.0e12 m^-3) directly.\n\nObservability classification: this component is purely algebraic \u2014 both equations are `~` assignment relations with no `D(.)` time-derivative operator, so the `(t)` time index has no dynamical role and every trajectory is constant in time. Test and example scenarios use time_span [0.0, 1.0] and sample at t=0, mirroring the convention of sibling observed-only ESM files (ope.esm, oh_production.esm, gwp.esm).\n\nEquation cascade: the two equations form a topologically-ordered cascade \u2014 k_eff depends only on the parameter k_OH and the input OH_conc; tau_OH depends on k_eff. tau_OH's equation is written `tau_OH ~ 1 / k_eff` (referencing the k_eff output) rather than fully inlined as 1/(k_OH*OH_conc) \u2014 this preserves the upstream symbolic structure, which splits the lifetime into an explicit pseudo-first-order rate constant k_eff and its reciprocal, mirroring the ope.esm `OPE ~ P_O3/L_NOx` and oh_production.esm cascade convention.\n\nNumerical defaults: the upstream input @variable OH_conc and @parameter k_OH carry no defaults \u2014 the .esm defaults are taken from the canonical upstream verification test `2.9 Eq. 2.12: OH Reaction Lifetime` (test/atmospheric_lifetime_test.jl), the methane scenario:\n  k_OH    = 6.3e-21 m^3/s   (methane + OH; upstream CGS 6.3e-15 cm^3/molec/s)\n  OH_conc = 1.0e12 m^-3     (global tropospheric mean OH; upstream CGS 1.0e6 molec/cm^3)\nAt these defaults k_eff = 6.3e-9 s^-1 and tau_OH = 158730158.73015872 s ~= 5.03 Julian years \u2014 the canonical methane OH-lifetime. Methane is the textbook illustration of an OH-controlled lifetime; the upstream docstring's stated 'tau: seconds to years' range is anchored at its long-lived end by exactly this CH4 case.\n\nUpstream test reproduction:\n- `1.4 OHReactionLifetime Structure` (test/atmospheric_lifetime_test.jl) \u2014 reproduced by the .esm structural shape (4 variables = 2 parameter + 2 state, 2 equations).\n- `2.9 Eq. 2.12: OH Reaction Lifetime` (test/atmospheric_lifetime_test.jl) \u2014 a pure-arithmetic verification of tau = 1/(k_OH*[OH]) for two species: methane (k_OH=6.3e-15 cm^3/molec/s, [OH]=1e6 molec/cm^3 -> tau ~= 5.0 years, upstream rtol=0.1) and carbon monoxide (k_OH=2.4e-13 cm^3/molec/s -> tau ~= 48 days, upstream rtol=0.1). Reproduced and tightened to rel=1e-10 by `upstream_eq212_methane_lifetime_defaults` (CH4, at the declared defaults) and `upstream_eq212_carbon_monoxide_lifetime` (CO, k_OH overridden to 2.4e-19 m^3/s). The CO pinned values are computed from the .esm's own SI literal 2.4e-19 m^3/s \u2014 k_eff = 2.4e-19*1.0e12 = 2.4000000000000003e-07 s^-1, tau_OH = 4166666.666666666 s \u2014 internally exact at rel=1e-10; this differs from the upstream CGS arithmetic 1/(2.4e-13*1e6) by one ULP (~2e-16 relative, six orders of magnitude below the upstream rtol=0.1).\nThe remaining eight tests extend coverage beyond the upstream suite: inverse scaling of tau_OH in OH_conc (doubled, halved), the k_OH<->OH_conc product symmetry (doubling k_OH gives a lifetime bit-identical to doubling OH_conc), the docstring's stated k_OH range endpoints (1e-14 and 1e-10 cm^3/molec/s \u2014 slowly- and highly-reactive species), the clean-remote and polluted-daytime OH regimes, and a joint two-input perturbation.\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1.0e-10 / abs=1.0e-12): the two algebraic equations are minimal expression trees \u2014 k_eff is a single two-factor product (1 IEEE-754 op), tau_OH a single reciprocal (1 op). Each output is correctly-rounded to within ~1 ULP ~= 1e-16 relative; rel=1e-10 leaves six orders of magnitude of headroom and is far tighter than the upstream test 2.9's rtol=0.1. No test scenario produces a zero or near-zero output (the smallest pinned magnitudes are k_eff ~= 1e-4 s^-1 and tau_OH = 1e4 s, in the highly-reactive case), so the abs=1.0e-12 floor is never the binding tolerance; it is retained as a model-level floor matching the sibling observed-only ESM convention (ope.esm rel=1e-10/abs=1e-12, oh_production.esm rel=1e-10/abs=1e-12). The OH_conc->0 boundary (k_eff->0, tau_OH = 1/0 -> +Inf) is deliberately not exercised as a test scenario \u2014 a non-finite expected value has no meaningful rel/abs tolerance \u2014 and no example sweep reaches OH_conc = 0.\n\nUnit balance (verified): both equations balance dimensionally.\n  k_eff  `k_OH*OH_conc`: (m^3/s)*(m^-3) = s^-1 ok\n  tau_OH `1 / k_eff`: 1/(s^-1) = s ok (the literal 1 is dimensionless)\nAll number densities in SI m^-3, the rate constant in SI m^3/s, the effective first-order rate constant in s^-1, the lifetime in s. SI throughout; no unit conversion at parse or runtime."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1e-10,
                "abs": 1e-12
            },
            "variables": {
                "k_OH": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 6.3e-21,
                    "description": "Second-order (bimolecular) rate constant for the trace-species + OH reaction [m^3/s] (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006 Ch. 2, Eq. 2.12). The intrinsic OH reactivity of the species, which with the ambient OH concentration sets the effective first-order loss rate k_eff = k_OH*OH_conc. The default 6.3e-21 m^3/s is the methane + OH rate constant \u2014 the SI form of the upstream CGS value 6.3e-15 cm^3/molec/s (1 cm^3 = 1e-6 m^3, the dimensionless `molec` count dropped). The upstream docstring quotes a typical species range of 1e-14 to 1e-10 cm^3/molec/s (1e-20 to 1e-16 m^3/s); methane, exceptionally unreactive, sits just below it. Encoded as `type: parameter`: it is the component's sole upstream @parameter, set via parameter_overrides in tests and parameter sweeps in examples."
                },
                "OH_conc": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 1000000000000.0,
                    "description": "Ambient hydroxyl-radical number density [m^-3] (externally-supplied input). The default 1.0e12 m^-3 ~= 1e6 molec/cm^3 is the global tropospheric mean OH concentration and is the value used by the upstream verification test `2.9 Eq. 2.12` for both its methane and carbon-monoxide cases; it is the SI form of the upstream CGS 1.0e6 molec/cm^3 (1 cm^-3 = 1e6 m^-3). OH appears only in k_eff = k_OH*OH_conc, so the OH-reaction lifetime tau_OH is exactly inversely proportional to OH_conc \u2014 a higher ambient OH burden shortens the lifetime of every species. Encoded as `type: parameter` (not `type: state`) because OHReactionLifetime has no governing equation for OH_conc \u2014 it is an externally-supplied input variable, resolved into a parameter by the canonical mtkcompile(sys; inputs=[OH_conc]) compile path."
                },
                "k_eff": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "s^-1",
                    "description": "Effective pseudo-first-order rate constant for loss by OH reaction [s^-1]: k_eff = k_OH*OH_conc. Collapses the second-order reaction X + OH into a first-order decay constant for X by absorbing the (approximately constant) OH concentration \u2014 the standard pseudo-first-order treatment, consistent with Eq. 2.6 of Seinfeld & Pandis (2006). At the methane default scenario k_eff = 6.3e-9 s^-1. Exactly linear in both k_OH and OH_conc."
                },
                "tau_OH": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "s",
                    "description": "Atmospheric lifetime of the trace species against removal by reaction with OH [s] (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006 Ch. 2, Eq. 2.12): tau_OH = 1/k_eff = 1/(k_OH*[OH]). The e-folding time for first-order decay of the species under OH oxidation. At the methane default scenario tau_OH ~= 1.587e8 s ~= 5.03 years; carbon monoxide (~38x more reactive) is ~48 days. Inversely proportional to both the species reactivity k_OH and the ambient OH concentration \u2014 the OH-reaction lifetime spans seconds (fast alkenes in polluted air) to years (CH4 in clean air)."
                }
            },
            "equations": [
                {
                    "lhs": "k_eff",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "*",
                        "args": [
                            "k_OH",
                            "OH_conc"
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "lhs": "tau_OH",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "/",
                        "args": [
                            1,
                            "k_eff"
                        ]
                    }
                }
            ],
            "tests": [
                {
                    "id": "upstream_eq212_methane_lifetime_defaults",
                    "description": "Reproduces and tightens the methane branch of the upstream `2.9 Eq. 2.12: OH Reaction Lifetime` test (GasChem.jl test/atmospheric_lifetime_test.jl). At the declared defaults k_OH=6.3e-21 m^3/s (methane + OH, upstream CGS 6.3e-15 cm^3/molec/s) and OH_conc=1.0e12 m^-3 (global tropospheric mean OH, upstream CGS 1.0e6 molec/cm^3): k_eff = k_OH*OH_conc = 6.3e-9 s^-1 and tau_OH = 1/k_eff = 158730158.73015872 s = 5.0299 Julian years. The upstream asserts tau_CH4 in years ~= 5.0 at rtol=0.1; this test pins both outputs to single-ULP precision at rel=1e-10, nine orders of magnitude tighter. Because nothing is overridden it also guards the k_OH and OH_conc defaults: any drift in either shifts both pinned values.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {},
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "k_eff",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 6.3e-09
                        },
                        {
                            "variable": "tau_OH",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 158730158.73015872
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "upstream_eq212_carbon_monoxide_lifetime",
                    "description": "Reproduces and tightens the carbon-monoxide branch of the upstream `2.9 Eq. 2.12` test. k_OH overridden to 2.4e-19 m^3/s (CO + OH, upstream CGS 2.4e-13 cm^3/molec/s), OH_conc at the default 1.0e12 m^-3. k_eff = 2.4000000000000003e-07 s^-1, tau_OH = 4166666.666666666 s = 48.2253 days. The upstream asserts tau_CO in days ~= 48 at rtol=0.1; this test pins both outputs at rel=1e-10. The pinned values are computed from the .esm's own SI literal 2.4e-19; they differ from the upstream CGS arithmetic 1/(2.4e-13*1e6) by one ULP (~2e-16 relative), six orders of magnitude inside the upstream rtol=0.1. CO is ~38x more reactive toward OH than CH4, so its OH lifetime is ~38x shorter (weeks, not years).",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "k_OH": 2.4e-19
                    },
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "k_eff",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 2.4000000000000003e-07
                        },
                        {
                            "variable": "tau_OH",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 4166666.666666666
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "oh_conc_doubled_halves_lifetime",
                    "description": "OH_conc doubled to 2.0e12 m^-3, k_OH at the CH4 default. k_eff = k_OH*OH_conc is exactly linear in OH_conc, so k_eff doubles to 1.26e-8 s^-1 and tau_OH = 1/k_eff halves to 79365079.36507936 s (2.515 yr). Verifies the inverse proportionality tau_OH ~ 1/[OH]: a more oxidising (higher-OH) atmosphere removes the trace species twice as fast.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "OH_conc": 2000000000000.0
                    },
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "k_eff",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 1.26e-08
                        },
                        {
                            "variable": "tau_OH",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 79365079.36507936
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "oh_conc_halved_doubles_lifetime",
                    "description": "OH_conc halved to 5.0e11 m^-3, k_OH at the CH4 default. k_eff halves to 3.15e-9 s^-1 and tau_OH doubles to 317460317.46031743 s (10.06 yr). The downward-OH counterpart of `oh_conc_doubled_halves_lifetime` \u2014 together they bracket the default scenario and confirm tau_OH is exactly inversely proportional to the ambient OH concentration.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "OH_conc": 500000000000.0
                    },
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
